\section{Parsing submitted answers}

The HTTP handler receives raw form fields from the network, not trusted
Python values.  We validate them in [[_parse_answer()]] so
[[store.record()]] and the results view can assume that every recorded
answer could have come from the form the presenter served.

That boundary matters most for multiple-choice polls.  A crafted request
could otherwise submit an out-of-range option index, omit every value for
a multi-select poll, or repeat the same checkbox value to make one
respondent count twice for the same option.  Rejecting those shapes here
keeps the stored answers aligned with the per-respondent percentages the
results view reports.

Open questions now accept uploaded text files as an alternative to pasted text.
That keeps long answers workable on phones, where copying a code file or essay
into a textarea is often awkward.  File uploads switch the browser to multipart
encoding, so the first helper below translates that body back into the same
[[dict[str, list[str]]]] shape that [[parse_qs()]] already returns.  Uploaded
file fields carry their sanitized basename as the first line of the field value;
keeping the name adjacent to the body prevents crafted multipart forms from
mixing one file's text with another file's label.

The parser stays in the standard library.  [[cgi.FieldStorage]] used to be the
obvious option, but it is deprecated and disappearing from newer Python
versions.  [[BytesParser]] and [[default_policy]] give us MIME parsing without
adding a framework dependency.

Browsers usually omit a charset for uploaded files, so UTF-8 is the important
default.  If decoding fails, we reject the upload explicitly instead of storing
garbled text.

<<constants>>=
MIN_FORM_BODY_BYTES = 64 * 1024
MULTIPART_SLACK_BYTES = 4096
UPLOAD_FALLBACK_NAME = "upload"
@

<<functions>>=


def _parse_multipart(
    content_type: str, body: bytes
) -> dict[str, list[str]]:
    """Return form fields parsed from a multipart/form-data body."""

    message = BytesParser(policy=default_policy).parsebytes(
        b"Content-Type: "
        + content_type.encode("utf-8")
        + b"\r\nMIME-Version: 1.0\r\n\r\n"
        + body
    )
    if not message.is_multipart():
        raise ValueError("malformed multipart form data")

    fields: dict[str, list[str]] = {}
    for part in message.iter_parts():
        if part.get_content_disposition() != "form-data":
            raise ValueError("malformed multipart form data")

        name = part.get_param("name", header="content-disposition")
        if not name:
            raise ValueError("malformed multipart form data")

        payload = part.get_payload(decode=True) or b""
        charset = part.get_param("charset", header="content-type") or "utf-8"
        try:
            text = payload.decode(charset)
        except (LookupError, UnicodeDecodeError) as err:
            raise ValueError(
                "uploaded file is not valid text; save it as UTF-8"
            ) from err

        filename = part.get_filename()
        if filename is not None:
            if part.defects:
                raise ValueError("malformed multipart form data")
            safe_name = (
                os.path.basename(filename or UPLOAD_FALLBACK_NAME)
                or UPLOAD_FALLBACK_NAME
            )
            if "\r" in safe_name or "\n" in safe_name:
                raise ValueError("malformed multipart form data")
            fields.setdefault(name, []).append(f"{safe_name}\n{text}")
        else:
            fields.setdefault(name, []).append(text)

    return fields
@

Markdown fences need one extra care point: uploaded source files may already
contain backticks.  We therefore choose a closing fence that is strictly longer
than the longest backtick run in the body, which is the CommonMark rule that
keeps the outer fence from terminating early.

<<functions>>=


def _fence_block(fence_lang: str | None, body: str) -> str:
    if fence_lang is None:
        return body

    longest_run = 0
    current_run = 0
    for char in body:
        if char == "`":
            current_run += 1
            longest_run = max(longest_run, current_run)
        else:
            current_run = 0

    fence = "`" * max(3, longest_run + 1)
    return f"{fence}{fence_lang}\n{body}\n{fence}"
@

The request-size cap has to cover three different shapes.  Ordinary
multiple-choice and scale posts are tiny, so we keep a [[64 * 1024]]
floor that accepts them without looking at question-specific limits.
Open and word-cloud questions both carry text bodies bounded by
[[max_chars]], so we add a [[* 4]] multiplier for the UTF-8 worst case
and leave a little multipart framing slack on top.  The slack is
unnecessary for word-cloud posts (they use plain URL encoding rather
than multipart), but reusing the same headroom is cheaper than carving
out a second formula for a few hundred bytes.

<<functions>>=


def _max_request_body(question) -> int:
    if isinstance(question, (OpenQuestion, WordCloudQuestion)):
        max_chars = question.max_chars
    else:
        max_chars = 0
    return max(
        max_chars * 4 + MULTIPART_SLACK_BYTES,
        MIN_FORM_BODY_BYTES,
    )
@

The final parser step normalises all question kinds into the values the store
records.  For open questions, that means combining the textarea text and an
optional uploaded file into one string.  We keep the uploaded basename but strip
any path components so a browser or crafted client cannot smuggle [[../]] into
the recorded label.

Word-cloud questions deliberately use their own short arm rather than
sharing the open-question branch.  A word cloud aggregates tokens from
many short answers; piping a file body into that flow would either dump
a hundred tokens from one respondent or treat the whole file body as a
single token, neither of which matches what authors mean by a
word-cloud poll.  The arm therefore reads only the textarea value,
enforces [[max_chars]] directly, and returns the raw string.

<<functions>>=


def _parse_answer(question, fields: dict[str, list[str]]) -> Any:
    if isinstance(question, MCQuestion):
        values = fields.get("value", [])
        if question.multi:
            if not values:
                raise ValueError("choose at least one option")

            indices = [int(value) for value in values]
            if any(index < 0 or index >= len(question.options)
                   for index in indices):
                raise ValueError(
                    "multiple-choice answer outside the allowed range"
                )
            if len(set(indices)) != len(indices):
                raise ValueError(
                    "multiple-choice answer repeats the same option"
                )
            return indices
        if len(values) != 1:
            raise ValueError("choose exactly one option")
        index = int(values[0])
        if index < 0 or index >= len(question.options):
            raise ValueError(
                "multiple-choice answer outside the allowed range"
            )
        return index

    if isinstance(question, OpenQuestion):
        text = fields.get("value", [""])[0]
        file_upload = fields.get("file", [""])[0]
        filename = UPLOAD_FALLBACK_NAME
        file_text = ""
        if file_upload:
            filename, _separator, file_text = file_upload.partition("\n")
            filename = filename or UPLOAD_FALLBACK_NAME

        if text and file_text:
            value = (
                f"Text: {text}\n\n"
                f"File {filename}:\n{_fence_block(question.fence, file_text)}"
            )
        elif file_text:
            value = (
                f"File {filename}:\n"
                f"{_fence_block(question.fence, file_text)}"
            )
        else:
            value = text

        if len(value) > question.max_chars:
            raise ValueError("text answer too long")
        return value

    if isinstance(question, WordCloudQuestion):
        text = fields.get("value", [""])[0]
        if len(text) > question.max_chars:
            raise ValueError("text answer too long")
        return text

    value = int(fields.get("value", [str(question.low)])[0])
    if value < question.low or value > question.high:
        raise ValueError("scale answer outside the allowed range")
    return value
