\subsection{Per-type stats lines}

Multiple-choice questions get a mode callout: which option the class
landed on most.  Scale questions get the descriptive statistics inline
in one row.  Open questions get the average answer length.  Each helper
returns an empty string when there are no answers, so the page degrades
gracefully to just the window filter and the \enquote{Total responses:
0} line.

<<functions>>=
def _render_mc_stats(
    question: MCQuestion, summary: dict[str, Any]
) -> str:
    mode_index = summary.get("mode_index")
    if mode_index is None:
        return ""
    label = question.options[mode_index]
    percentage = summary["percentages"][mode_index]
    return (
        f'<p class="mode-callout">'
        f'Mode: <strong>{escape(label)}</strong> '
        f'({percentage:.0f}%)'
        f'</p>'
    )
@

<<functions>>=
def _render_scale_stats(summary: dict[str, Any]) -> str:
    if summary.get("mean") is None:
        return ""
    pairs = [
        ("Mean", f'{summary["mean"]:.2f}'),
        ("Median", f'{summary["median"]}'),
        ("Std", f'{summary["stddev"]:.2f}'),
        ("Min", f'{summary["min"]}'),
        ("Max", f'{summary["max"]}'),
    ]
    body = " · ".join(
        f'<span class="stat-label">{label}:</span> '
        f'<strong>{value}</strong>'
        for label, value in pairs
    )
    return f'<p class="stats">{body}</p>'
@

<<functions>>=
def _render_open_stats(summary: dict[str, Any]) -> str:
    avg = summary.get("avg_length")
    if avg is None:
        return ""
    return (
        f'<p class="stats">'
        f'<span class="stat-label">Avg length:</span> '
        f'<strong>{avg:.0f}</strong> chars'
        f'</p>'
    )
@

\subsection{Markdown for free-text answers}

Free-text answers benefit from light formatting---emphasis, lists, code
spans, links to references---so they read as prose rather than as a wall
of plain text.  Markdown is the de-facto convention for that, and
[[markdown-it-py]] is a pure-Python CommonMark engine without external
binaries to install.

The danger of rendering user-submitted content is XSS.  We close the common
vectors at the markdown boundary:
\begin{description}
\item[Raw HTML] [[html=False]] makes the parser escape any literal
  [[<script>]], [[<iframe>]], or other tag in the input.
\item[Hostile URLs] An explicit allow-list of [[http]], [[https]], and
  [[mailto]] sits in front of the engine's default validator (which
  already blocks [[javascript:]], [[vbscript:]], [[data:]], and
  [[file:]] URLs).  Replacing the default with an explicit allow-list
  keeps the policy auditable in one place and prevents a future library
  upgrade from quietly broadening the accepted scheme set.
\item[Remote images] The image rule is disabled, because an [[<img>]]
  emitted from respondent markdown would make every results-page viewer
  fetch attacker-chosen URLs.
\end{description}
Storage stays as the raw markdown source; rendering happens only at
view time, so the JSON export remains a faithful, lossless copy of what
the student typed.

Syntax highlighting for fenced code blocks uses Pygments.  The
[[_highlight_code]] callback receives the raw code content and the
language name from the fenced-block marker.  When Pygments knows the
language it returns a complete [[<pre><code>]] block with inline
[[<span>]] elements; returning an empty string signals the renderer
to fall back to its own plain-text escape, so unrecognised languages
are still safe.  [[PYGMENTS_CSS]] is generated once at import time
from the same [[_FORMATTER]] instance used at render time, guaranteeing
the stylesheet and the highlighted spans always agree.

<<constants>>=
_FORMATTER = _HtmlFormatter(nowrap=True)
PYGMENTS_CSS = _FORMATTER.get_style_defs(".highlight")


def _highlight_code(content: str, lang: str, attrs: str) -> str:
    """Return Pygments-highlighted HTML for ``content``, or '' to skip."""
    if not lang:
        return ""
    try:
        lexer = get_lexer_by_name(lang, stripall=False)
    except ClassNotFound:
        return ""
    return (
        f'<pre><code class="language-{lang} highlight">'
        + _pygments_highlight(content, lexer, _FORMATTER)
        + "</code></pre>"
    )


@

<<constants>>=
_MARKDOWN = MarkdownIt(
    "commonmark",
    {
        "html": False,
        "linkify": False,
        "typographer": False,
        "highlight": _highlight_code,
    },
).disable("image")

_SAFE_URL_SCHEMES = {"http", "https", "mailto"}
@

The validator runs on every link the parser sees and is bound to
[[_MARKDOWN]] once at import time.  A relative URL (no colon) is
rejected: the polling server does not host arbitrary local pages, and
resolving relative links at render time is outside the threat model.

<<functions>>=
def _is_safe_url(url: str) -> bool:
    if ":" not in url:
        return False
    scheme = url.split(":", 1)[0].strip().lower()
    return scheme in _SAFE_URL_SCHEMES


_MARKDOWN.validateLink = _is_safe_url


def _render_open_answer_markdown(text: str) -> str:
    """Render a student's free-text answer as safe HTML."""
    return _MARKDOWN.render(text)
@

