\subsection{Rendering open-text answers}

Each answer becomes one [[<li>]] containing the markdown-rendered HTML.
The wrapping class lets the stylesheet tighten margins on inner
[[<p>]], [[<ul>]], and [[<ol>]] so multi-paragraph answers do not
sprawl across the page.  The previously rendered ISO timestamp is gone
from this view---it remains in the JSON export for downstream analysis,
but a screen full of timestamps does not help the lecturer scan
free-text reactions during a live lecture.

<<functions>>=
def _render_open_answers(answers: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> str:
    if not answers:
        return "<p>No free-text answers yet.</p>"
    items = "".join(
        f'<li class="md-answer">'
        f'{_render_open_answer_markdown(answer["value"])}'
        f'</li>'
        for answer in answers
    )
    return f'<ol>{items}</ol>'
@

\subsection{Word-cloud results}

A word-cloud results view has two halves: a one-line summary of how
busy the cloud is, and a visualisation chosen by the author at slide
time.  We keep the summary identical across visualisations so a
lecturer comparing modes does not have to relearn what the numbers mean.

The stats helper surfaces [[unique_words]] and [[total_tokens]] from the
aggregated summary.  The two numbers together describe the shape of
the answer set: a sparse, varied cloud has [[unique_words]] close to
[[total_tokens]]; a clustered cloud has [[total_tokens]] much larger.

<<functions>>=
def _render_wordcloud_stats(summary: dict[str, Any]) -> str:
    if not summary.get("total_tokens"):
        return ""
    return (
        f'<p class="stats">'
        f'<span class="stat-label">Words:</span> '
        f'<strong>{summary["total_tokens"]}</strong> · '
        f'<span class="stat-label">Distinct:</span> '
        f'<strong>{summary["unique_words"]}</strong>'
        f'</p>'
    )
@

The dispatcher still chooses the visual form strictly by
[[question.render]] because the question validates that field at
construction time.  Only the [[svg]] arm needs an internal fallback:
the public render value stays stable, but the implementation now
prefers the optional [[wordcloud]] package when it is installed and
otherwise keeps using Mentipy's built-in SVG layout.  The visual modes
append the same frequency table as [[render="table"]], so the lecturer
keeps exact counts while still seeing the overall shape.

<<functions>>=
def _render_wordcloud(
    question: WordCloudQuestion,
    frequencies: list[list[Any]],
) -> str:
    if not frequencies:
        return "<p>No answers yet.</p>"
    pairs = [(str(word), int(count)) for word, count in frequencies]
    if question.render == "table":
        return _render_wordcloud_table(pairs)
    if question.render == "scaled":
        visual = _render_wordcloud_scaled(pairs)
    else:
        visual = _render_wordcloud_svg(pairs)
    return visual + _render_wordcloud_table(pairs)
@

\subsubsection{Font scaling}

All three renderers share one helper that maps a frequency to a font
size.  We use a linear scale rather than a logarithm because the
classroom answer counts we expect (single-digit per word, double-digit
totals) are too small for a log curve to add useful resolution --- the
top word would dominate visually only marginally over the second, and
the tail would all look the same size.  When every word has the same
count we collapse to the middle of the range so the cloud reads as
uniform rather than pegged to the maximum.

<<functions>>=
def _wordcloud_font_scale(
    counts: list[int],
    *,
    min_size: float,
    max_size: float,
) -> list[float]:
    low, high = min(counts), max(counts)
    if low == high:
        return [(min_size + max_size) / 2 for _ in counts]
    span = high - low
    return [
        min_size + (count - low) / span * (max_size - min_size)
        for count in counts
    ]
@

\subsubsection{Table mode}

The table view is the plainest renderer.  It is also the most useful
when the answers are sparse or the lecturer wants a quick numerical
overview rather than a visual one --- showing the leaderboard, the
total count, and each word's share rather than the gestalt.

<<functions>>=
def _render_wordcloud_table(pairs: list[tuple[str, int]]) -> str:
    total = sum(count for _, count in pairs)
    rows = "".join(
        f"<tr><td>{escape(word)}</td><td>{count}</td>"
        f"<td>{count / total * 100:.1f}%</td></tr>"
        for word, count in pairs
    )
    return (
        '<table class="wordcloud-table">'
        "<thead><tr><th>Word</th>"
        f"<th>Count ({total})</th>"
        "<th>Percentage</th></tr></thead>"
        f"<tbody>{rows}</tbody>"
        "</table>"
    )
@

\subsubsection{Scaled inline list}

The scaled inline list is a CSS-only cloud: each word becomes a span
with [[font-size]] in [[em]] units proportional to its count.  We
target inline rendering (a row of words that wraps naturally) because
the alternative --- a CSS grid or a custom layout --- would add styling
the project does not currently carry.

<<functions>>=
def _render_wordcloud_scaled(pairs: list[tuple[str, int]]) -> str:
    counts = [count for _, count in pairs]
    sizes = _wordcloud_font_scale(counts, min_size=0.9, max_size=2.6)
    spans = "".join(
        f'<span class="wordcloud-word" '
        f'style="font-size: {size:.2f}em">{escape(word)}</span>'
        for (word, _count), size in zip(pairs, sizes)
    )
    return f'<div class="wordcloud-scaled">{spans}</div>'
@

\subsubsection{SVG mode}

The SVG view is the default because authors who think \enquote{word
cloud} usually picture a single graphic they can copy into a slide.
When the optional [[wordcloud]] package is installed, we let it do the
placement because its packed layout is denser and more recognisably a
word cloud than our small home-grown fallback.  The package stays
optional because it brings in NumPy, Pillow, and Matplotlib; users who
only need the built-in renderers should not pay that dependency cost.

A live results page refreshes every two seconds, so the package-backed
layout must be deterministic.  We fix its random seed, keep the words
horizontal, and normalise the returned SVG fragment so the HTML
contract stays the same: one inline [[<svg>]] with the
[[wordcloud-svg]] CSS hook and an accessible label.

<<functions>>=
def _render_wordcloud_svg(pairs: list[tuple[str, int]]) -> str:
    svg = _render_wordcloud_svg_with_package(pairs)
    if svg is not None:
        return svg
    return _render_wordcloud_svg_fallback(pairs)
@

The optional-package path is an optimisation, not a requirement.  A
missing dependency is normal, so [[ImportError]] simply returns
[[None]] and lets the caller fall back to Mentipy's own SVG layout.

<<functions>>=
def _render_wordcloud_svg_with_package(
    pairs: list[tuple[str, int]],
) -> str | None:
    try:
        module = importlib.import_module("wordcloud")
    except ImportError:
        return None

    cloud = module.WordCloud(
        width=720,
        height=480,
        background_color=None,
        mode="RGBA",
        color_func=lambda *_args, **_kwargs: "#111",
        prefer_horizontal=1.0,
        random_state=0,
    )
    svg = cloud.generate_from_frequencies(dict(pairs)).to_svg().lstrip()
    if svg.startswith("<?xml"):
        _declaration, _separator, svg = svg.partition("?>")
        svg = svg.lstrip()
    return svg.replace(
        "<svg",
        (
            '<svg class="wordcloud-svg" role="img" '
            'aria-label="Word cloud"'
        ),
        1,
    )
@

The built-in fallback still uses a flow layout.  A true spiral packer
would require font-metric estimation that is wrong for diacritics and
adds far more code than the rest of this renderer combined, so we place
words left-to-right and wrap onto a new line when they would overflow.
Each word's bounding-box width is approximated as
[[0.6 * font\_size * len(word)]], a heuristic that is accurate enough
for Latin and mixed Latin-Cyrillic text to avoid most overlaps.
Full-width scripts (CJK, fullwidth Latin) will underflow the estimate
and may overlap; installing the optional [[wordcloud]] package
switches to a glyph-aware packer that handles them correctly.

We also leave a little more outer padding than the heuristic strictly
needs.  Browser font metrics differ by a few pixels at the edge of the
[[viewBox]], and a slightly wider gutter is cheaper than clipping the
last stroke of a tall or wide glyph.

Every word passes through [[escape]] before reaching the [[<text>]]
element because the words come from respondent input --- an unescaped
[[<]] would terminate the SVG element and let a respondent inject
arbitrary markup.

<<functions>>=
def _render_wordcloud_svg_fallback(
    pairs: list[tuple[str, int]],
) -> str:
    counts = [count for _, count in pairs]
    sizes = _wordcloud_font_scale(counts, min_size=14.0, max_size=48.0)
    canvas_width = 720.0
    padding = 16.0
    line_gap = 1.25
    elements: list[str] = []
    cursor_x = padding
    cursor_y = padding
    line_height = 0.0
    for (word, count), size in zip(pairs, sizes):
        width = max(size * 0.6 * len(word), size)
        if cursor_x + width > canvas_width - padding and elements:
            cursor_x = padding
            cursor_y += line_height * line_gap
            line_height = 0.0
        elements.append(
            f'<text x="{cursor_x:.1f}" '
            f'y="{cursor_y + size:.1f}" '
            f'font-size="{size:.1f}" '
            f'class="wordcloud-word">{escape(word)}</text>'
        )
        cursor_x += width + size * 0.4
        line_height = max(line_height, size)
    height = cursor_y + line_height + padding
    return (
        f'<svg class="wordcloud-svg" '
        f'viewBox="0 0 {canvas_width:.0f} {height:.0f}" '
        f'xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" '
        f'role="img" aria-label="Word cloud">'
        + "".join(elements)
        + "</svg>"
    )
@

Let's verify both SVG branches directly before the end-to-end page
tests.  The optional package path should preserve Mentipy's HTML hook,
while the live results page still needs a deterministic fallback test
that does not depend on the package being installed in the test
